{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474122"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11784"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11784"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.11,0.01,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111779"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4398"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93849"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1651"},{"type":"tags","id":"3521"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41699"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111779"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother who is concerned about his height. He has always been on the 70th percentile for height but over the last year he has grown rapidly and is now 165 cm tall (\u003E99th percentile). His mother is also concerned that he has been gaining weight. The boy reports being bullied at school, with other children calling him names due to his large hands and forehead. He also reports daily headaches for the past two months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. He is 165 cm tall with an arm span of 163 cm. He has large hands with thick fingers, prognathism, and frontal bossing. Visual field testing reveals reduced peripheral vision. He has Tanner stage 2 pubic hair. Initial blood tests show elevated insulin-like growth factor 1 levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following visual field defects is most likely to be present in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bitemporal hemianopia","Homonymous hemianopia","Altitudinal defect","Central scotoma","Peripheral constriction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy presents with features highly suggestive of gigantism, a rare disorder caused by excess growth hormone secretion before epiphyseal closure. The combination of excessive linear growth, acral enlargement (large hands with thick fingers), facial changes (prognathism and frontal bossing), and signs of pituitary mass effect (headaches) points strongly to this diagnosis. The elevated insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) levels confirm growth hormone excess. Gigantism is most commonly caused by a growth hormone-secreting pituitary adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBitemporal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic visual field defect seen in pituitary adenomas. This occurs because the pituitary gland is located directly inferior to the optic chiasm, where the nasal fibers of each optic nerve cross. As a pituitary adenoma enlarges superiorly, it compresses the crossing fibers at the chiasm, resulting in loss of vision in the temporal fields of both eyes. This pattern is pathognomonic for a lesion affecting the optic chiasm and is a key diagnostic feature of pituitary adenomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to loss of the same half of the visual field in both eyes (either both right or both left fields). This pattern occurs with lesions posterior to the optic chiasm, typically in the optic tract, optic radiations, or visual cortex, rather than from a pituitary lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAltitudinal defect\u003C/strong\u003E is a horizontal visual field defect affecting either the upper or lower half of the visual field in one or both eyes. This pattern is typically seen with lesions affecting the retina or optic nerve, such as ischemic optic neuropathy or branch retinal artery occlusion, not with pituitary lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral scotoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a visual field defect affecting central vision while peripheral vision remains intact. This pattern is typically seen with lesions affecting the macula or the maculopapillary bundle of the optic nerve, such as optic neuritis or toxic/nutritional optic neuropathies, not with pituitary lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral constriction\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a concentric narrowing of the visual field with preservation of central vision. This pattern can be seen in conditions such as glaucoma, retinitis pigmentosa, or certain types of drug toxicity, but is not characteristic of pituitary lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bitemporal hemianopia is the classic visual field defect in pituitary adenomas due to compression of the optic chiasm.","Gigantism is caused by excess growth hormone secretion before epiphyseal closure, typically from a pituitary adenoma.","Clinical features of gigantism include excessive linear growth, acral enlargement, and symptoms of pituitary mass effect."],"references":["Barstow C, Rerucha C. Evaluation of Short and Tall Stature in Children. Am Fam Physician. 2015;92(1):43-50","Eugster EA, Pescovitz OH. Gigantism. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 1999;84(12):4379-84."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93849"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11784"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93849"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T19:26:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T19:28:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4398"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111779"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}